Considering the presence of neonatal diarrhea in calves with varying titers of colostrum Abs, it was observed that all calves were affected by one, two or even three events of severe diarrhea with an average duration of 18 days (Table 2
); BCoV shedding of short time duration (2–3 days) was detected in 10% (3/30) of calves (Table 1, Table 2) and the highest BCoV infectious titer was 105
 FFU/ml of stool. Although viral shedding was detected at a low rate in the calves’ stool, BCoV IgG1 seroconversion was observed in 42% of animals, suggesting that almost half of the calves were exposed to BCoV (Table 1).
